        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-6">Executive Research: Emerging Trends Shaping Doctoral Inquiry in 2026</h1>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-4 pb-6 border-b border-border">
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold">Prof. Stanley Oliver</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-muted">Principal, Brenkley Doctoral College</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none space-y-6 text-muted">

        <p class="text-lg font-medium text-foreground">The doctoral research questions that senior professionals bring to DCUK are a reliable leading indicator of where management thinking is heading. Over the past eighteen months, the concentration of research interests arriving at our admissions conversations has shifted markedly. Five trends, in particular, stand out — not as passing interests but as substantive, sustained areas of inquiry with implications for organisations, leadership practice, and professional education.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">1. AI Governance and Organisational Accountability</h2>

        <p>No trend features more prominently in current executive research interests than artificial intelligence governance. But it is important to be precise about what this means in a doctoral research context, because the surface-level interest in "AI" conceals several quite distinct research questions.</p>

        <p>The most compelling research questions are not about AI technology itself — those belong to computer science and engineering — but about the organisational and governance challenges that AI adoption creates. How do organisations assign accountability for AI-generated decisions? What frameworks allow boards and senior leaders to provide meaningful oversight of AI systems they do not technically understand? How do human workers integrate AI tools into professional practice without losing the expertise and judgement that make their roles valuable?</p>

        <p>These are precisely the questions that practitioner-researchers are positioned to address. A Chief Digital Officer pursuing a DBA on AI governance decision-making in financial services, or a hospital Chief Executive examining accountability frameworks for clinical AI tools — these are research projects that can generate genuinely original and applicable knowledge. We are supporting several researchers in this space at DCUK, and the quality of inquiry is high.</p>

        <p>The theoretical frameworks most useful here draw from institutional theory, principal-agent theory, sensemaking frameworks, and emerging work on algorithmic accountability. The methodological challenge is significant — this is fast-moving territory — but that makes careful, theoretically grounded empirical work all the more valuable.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">2. Climate-Resilient Leadership</h2>

        <p>The second emerging trend is the intersection of climate change and leadership — specifically, what it means to lead organisations through the physical, regulatory, and reputational pressures that climate transition is generating.</p>

        <p>This is not simply a question of sustainability strategy. It is a leadership question. Senior executives are increasingly being asked to navigate genuinely unprecedented situations: board expectations around scope 3 emissions they cannot directly control; workforce expectations about organisational values that may conflict with profitable business lines; regulatory environments that are changing faster than organisational adaptation can follow; and the human complexity of leading large workforces through transitions that will change how work is done.</p>

        <p>Doctoral research in this space is emerging from professionals across sectors — from NHS Chief Executives grappling with sustainability targets in a resource-constrained system, to property developers managing the complex ethics of regeneration projects in flood-risk areas. The common thread is the need for evidence about what effective leadership actually looks like in these conditions, as opposed to what it should look like in theory.</p>

        <p>Methodologically, this area lends itself to narrative inquiry, phenomenological approaches, and longitudinal case study work. The lived experience of leaders navigating climate-related pressures is rich qualitative territory, and the gap between the academic sustainability management literature and the practice reality remains substantial.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">3. Psychological Safety in Hybrid and Remote Organisations</h2>

        <p>Amy Edmondson's concept of psychological safety — the belief that one can speak up without fear of punishment or humiliation — has been one of the most influential ideas in organisational research of the past decade. But the research base was largely developed in co-located, synchronous working environments. The shift to hybrid and remote work has created entirely new conditions for psychological safety, and the evidence on how it operates in these conditions is sparse.</p>

        <p>Practitioner-researchers are bringing sharply pointed questions to this area. How does a manager create and maintain psychological safety in a team they may meet in person only quarterly? What happens to informal feedback loops, the casual corridor conversations that allow people to raise concerns before they become crises, when those conversations have no natural home? How does the visibility asymmetry of hybrid work — where remote workers are literally less visible than their in-office colleagues — affect who feels safe to speak up?</p>

        <p>These questions sit at the intersection of organisational behaviour, leadership, and work design. They are also questions where the research gap has real and immediate practical consequences. Leaders who do not understand how to create psychological safety in their particular work environment are leading teams where problems go unreported and potential goes unexpressed.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">4. Digital Transformation Leadership in Non-Profit and Public Sectors</h2>

        <p>The fourth trend is a counterpoint to the dominant narrative of digital transformation, which is typically told through the lens of private sector technology companies. A significant and growing body of practitioner-doctoral research is examining digital transformation in contexts where profit motives are absent, where accountability structures are political rather than commercial, and where the workforce may be less digitally native and more professionally protective of existing ways of working.</p>

        <p>Public sector and non-profit organisations face digital transformation challenges that are categorically different from those facing private sector organisations. They often lack the investment capacity for the rapid change cycles that technology vendors recommend. Their decision-making processes are slower by design. Their workforce relationships are more complex — trade union agreements, professional body regulations, and public service values all shape what change is possible and how quickly.</p>

        <p>Senior professionals in these sectors — NHS leaders, local government executives, charity chief executives, higher education administrators — are bringing research questions about digital leadership, change management, and technology adoption that the mainstream digital transformation literature, focused as it is on private sector cases, cannot answer. This is fertile and important territory for practitioner-research.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">5. Intergenerational Knowledge Transfer</h2>

        <p>The fifth trend is, in some ways, the most timeless — and yet it has acquired fresh urgency. As the baby boomer generation reaches the end of its working life, organisations across every sector are confronting the challenge of knowledge transfer at a scale and pace they have not previously encountered.</p>

        <p>This is not simply a human resources or succession planning problem, though it is partly that. It is a knowledge management challenge of the first order. The knowledge at risk is not primarily explicit — it is not the kind of knowledge that can be captured in a manual, a database, or a standard operating procedure. It is tacit: the pattern recognition of experienced professionals, the relationship intelligence of long-serving leaders, the contextual understanding of why things work the way they do in a particular organisation or sector.</p>

        <p>Practitioner-researchers in this space are examining questions that have direct and immediate relevance to their organisations. What knowledge transfer mechanisms actually work in professional services firms where senior partners are reluctant to share their client relationships? How does a school or multi-academy trust retain the pedagogical wisdom of experienced teachers when those teachers retire? What can be learned from sectors with long histories of apprenticeship models that might translate to knowledge-intensive professional environments?</p>

        <p>These are empirical questions with theoretical roots in knowledge management theory, communities of practice, and organisational learning. They are also questions where practitioner-researchers — often themselves the holders of the at-risk knowledge, or the leaders responsible for capturing it — have access and insight that externally-positioned researchers cannot replicate.</p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-foreground mt-8 mb-4">A Research Agenda Worth Pursuing</h2>

        <p>What connects these five trends is not a shared methodology or a common theoretical framework. It is a shared characteristic: they are all areas where the questions that matter most are being lived by the people inside organisations, and where the research that could answer them most usefully is practitioner-research.</p>

        <p>If any of these areas reflect questions you have been carrying — problems you have been sitting with professionally and wondering whether there might be a more rigorous way to address them — then doctoral study may be exactly the right next step. The questions are worth asking. The methods exist to address them. And the world has a use for the answers.</p>

